<section xml:id="sec-homo-non-homo" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>General <m>=</m> Homogeneous <m>+</m> Nonhomogeneous</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>If we return to the solution set in <xref ref="ex-large-linear-solution" /> in the previous
      section: <me>
        \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
        0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\0
        \end{bmatrix} x_2 +
        \begin{bmatrix}
        9 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0
        \end{bmatrix} x_4 +
        \begin{bmatrix}
        -46 \\ 0 \\ -13 \\ 0 \\ 9
        \end{bmatrix} \; | \; x_2, x_4 \in \mathbb{R} \right\}.
      </me>
      where the third vector is a particular solution and the other two vectors are multiplied by
      free variables (parameters). This form will give us a lot of information about the solution
      set. </p>

    <theorem>
      <p>The solution to a linear system can be described as <me>
          \{ \vec{p} + c_1 \vec{\beta}_1 + c_2 \vec{\beta}_2 + \cdots + c_n \vec{\beta}_n, \; | \;
        c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_n \in \mathbb{R} \}
        </me>
        where <m>\vec{p}</m> is any particular solution and the number of vectors <m>\vec{\beta}_1,
        \vec{\beta}_2, \ldots, \vec{\beta}_n</m> equals the number of free variables that the system
        has after Gaussian reduction (and in echelon form). </p>
    </theorem>


    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>A linear equation is <term>homogeneous</term> if the constant term (on the right hand
          side) is 0. A linear system is <term>homogeneous</term> if all constant terms is 0. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>The next two examples show the possible results of a homogeneous system. </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the solution to the linear system: <md>
            <mrow>2x - 3y \amp = 0, </mrow>
            <mrow>5x + 2y \amp =0,</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Using the row operation, <m>-5R_1 + 2R_2 \rightarrow R_2</m>, we get <md>
            <mrow>2x - 3y \amp = 0, </mrow>
            <mrow>0x + 19y \amp = 0,</mrow>
          </md> and from back substitution, we get the
          solution <m>(0,0)</m> and note that this is a unique solution. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-hydrazine-solution2">
      <statement>
        <p>Find the solution to the homogeneous linear system from <xref ref="ex-hydrazine" />. </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>k_1 \amp = 2k_3, </mrow>
            <mrow>3k_1 + 2k_2 \amp = 4k_3 + 2k_4, </mrow>
            <mrow>2k_2 \amp = k_4.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>In <xref ref="ex-hydrazine-solution" />, we wrote down the solution <me>
            \{ (k_4, \frac{1}{2} k_4, \frac{1}{2} k_4, k_4) \; | \; k_4 \in \mathbb{R} \},
          </me>
          In vector form the solution is <me>
            \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\ 1/2 \\ 1/2 \\ 1
            \end{bmatrix} k_4 \; | \; k_4 \in \mathbb{R} \right\}.
          </me>
          In this case, the solution set has an infinite number of points. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>


    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>For any homogeneous linear system there exist vectors <m>\vec{\beta}_1, \vec{\beta}_2,
          \ldots, \vec{\beta}_n</m> such that the solution set of the system is <me>
            \{ c_1 \vec{\beta}_1+c_2 \vec{\beta}_2 + \cdots + c_n \vec{\beta}_n\; | \; c_1, c_2,
          \ldots, c_n \in \mathbb{R} \}.
          </me></p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>First, use Gauss' method to reduce the linear system to echelon form.</p>

        <p>Let row <m>m</m> be the bottom-most row that is not in the form <m>0=0</m>, it will have
          the form: <me>
            a_{m,\ell_m} x_{\ell_m} + a_{m,\ell_m+1} x_{\ell_m+1} + \cdots + a_{m,n} x_n = 0
          </me>
          and since <m>x_{\ell_m}</m> is a leading variable <m>a_{m,\ell_m} \neq 0</m>. (Note: <m>
          \ell</m> means leading, so <m>\ell_m</m> means the column (variable \#) of the leading
          variable in the <m>m</m>th row.) Solving for <m>x_{\ell_m}</m>: <me>
            x_{\ell_m} = -\frac{a_{m,\ell_m+1}}{a_{m,\ell_m}} x_{\ell_m+1} - \cdots
          -\frac{a_{m,n}}{a_{m,\ell_m}} x_n
          </me></p>

        <p>This equation shows how to write <m>x_{\ell_m}</m> in terms of the free variables to the
          right of column <m>\ell_m</m>. There may or may not be free variables. If there are not
          then it says that <m>x_{\ell_m}=0</m>. </p>

        <p>Next, in the induction proof, assume that some row <m>t\leq m</m>, can be written <me>
          x_{\ell_t} = \text{linear combination of free variables}.
          </me>, then
          row <m>
            t-1</m> of the linear system in echelon form is: <me>
            a_{t-1,\ell_{t-1}} x_{\ell_{t-1}} + a_{t-1,\ell_{t-1}+1} x_{\ell_{t-1}+1} + \cdots +
          a_{t-1,n} x_n = 0
          </me>
          with <m>a_{t-1,\ell_{t-1}} \neq 0</m> and thus solve for <m>x_{\ell_{t-1}}</m> by
          subtracting all other terms and dividing through by <m>a_{t-1,\ell_{t-1}}</m>. Thus <m>
          x_{\ell_{t-1}}</m> is written as a linear combination of all variables to the right. For
          each leading variable on the right, replace it with its solution from back-substitution.
          Thus <m>x_{\ell_{t-1}}</m> can be written as <me>
            x_{\ell_{t-1}} = \text{linear combination of free variables}
          </me>
          Inductively, each leading variable can be written in this form. The <m>c_i</m> in the
          statement of the lemma are the free variables and the vectors <m>\vec{\beta}_i</m> are
          coefficients of the free variable corresponding to <m>c_i</m> in each <m>x_{\ell_i}</m>. </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsect-nonhomo-system">
    <title>Non-homogeneous Systems</title>

    <definition>
      <title>Homogeneous and Nonhomogeneous Systems</title>
      <statement>
        <p> If a system is not homogeneous, it is called <term>non-homogeneous</term>. For a
          non-homogeneous system, there is an <term>associated homogeneous system</term> found by
          replacing the right hand side with zeros. </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-nh-and-homo">
      <title>Solving a nonhomogeneous systems</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Solve <md>
            <mrow>x + 3y -z \amp = 9,</mrow>
            <mrow>+ y + 3z \amp = 6,</mrow>
            <mrow>x+4y +2z \amp = 15,</mrow>
          </md> and it's associated homogenous system. </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>First, we write the augmented coefficient matrix <me>
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 9 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 6 \\
            1 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 16
            \end{array}\right]
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          and then we put this matrix in row-reduced echelon form.
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>-R_1+R_3 \rightarrow R_3, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 9 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 6
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
            <mrow>-R_2 + R_3 \rightarrow R_3, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 9 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
            <mrow>-3R_2 + R_1 \rightarrow R_1, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 0 \amp -10 \amp -9 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p> Let <m>z=t</m> since it is a free variable and thus the solution can be written: </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> x \amp = 10 t -9</mrow>
            <mrow>y \amp = -3t+6</mrow>
            <mrow>z \amp = t </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          so the solution can be written in vector form as
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
            10 \\ -3 \\ 1
            \end{bmatrix} t + \begin{bmatrix}
            -9 \\ 6 \\ 0
            \end{bmatrix} \; | \; t \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p> and recall that <m>(-9,6,0)</m> is a particular solution. </p>

        <p>The associated homogeneous system is </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>x + 3y -z \amp = 0, </mrow>
            <mrow>+ y + 3z \amp = 0, </mrow>
            <mrow>x+4y +2z \amp = 0,</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          and the solution can be found by first writing the augmented coefficient matrix
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
            1 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 0
            \end{array}\right]
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          and then we put this matrix in row-reduced echelon form.
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>-R_1+R_3 \rightarrow R_3, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
            <mrow>-R_2 + R_3 \rightarrow R_3, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0\\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
            <mrow>-3R_2 + R_1 \rightarrow R_1, \qquad
              \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
              1 \amp 0 \amp -10 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
              \end{array}\right] </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p> which has the solution, using <m>z=t</m>
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> x \amp = 10 t </mrow>
            <mrow>y \amp = -3t </mrow>
            <mrow> z \amp = t </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          which can be written in vector form as
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
            10 \\ -3 \\ 1
            \end{bmatrix}z \; | \; z \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>


    <p>The above example indicates that a solution to non-homogeneous system
      consists of a particular solution and the solution to the associated
      homogeneous system. </p>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>For any linear system with a particular solution <m>\vec{p}</m>, the solution set is <me>
          \{ \vec{p} + \vec{h} \; | \; \vec{h}\; \text{satisfies the associated linear system} \}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p> To prove this, we will first show that any solution <m>\vec{s}</m> of the
          non-homogeneous linear system, <men xml:id="eq-nhs">
            a_{i,1} x_1 + a_{i,2} x_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} x_n = b_i \qquad \text{for}\;
            i=1,2,\ldots,m
          </men>
          then <m>\vec{s}-\vec{p}</m> satisfies the associated homogeneous system, <me>
            a_{i,1} x_1 + a_{i,2} x_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} x_n = 0 \qquad \text{for}\;
            i=1,2,\ldots,m
          </me>
          then show that if <m>\vec{h}</m> is a solution to the associated homogeneous system, then <m>
          \vec{h}+\vec{p}</m> satisfies the non-homogeneous system. </p>

        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>Assume that <m>\vec{s}=(s_1,s_2, \ldots,s_n)</m> satisfies (<xref ref="eq-nhs" />),
                that is </p>

              <p>
                <me>
                  a_{i,1} s_1 + a_{i,2} s_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} s_n = b_i \qquad \text{for}\;
                  i=1,2,\ldots,m,
                </me>
              </p>
              <p> then <m>\vec{s}-\vec{p}</m> satisfies </p>

              <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>a_{i,1} (s_1-p_1)\amp + a_{i,2}(s_2-p_2) + \cdots + a_{i,n}(s_n-p_n)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\qquad \amp =
                    a_{i,1} s_1 - a_{i,1} p_1 + a_{i,2} s_2 - a_{i,2} p_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} s_n -
                    a_{i,n} p_n </mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = (a_{i,1} s_1 + a_{i,2} s_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} s_n) - </mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp \qquad (a_{i,1} p_1 + a_{i,2} p_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} p_n) </mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = b_i - b_i = 0</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>

              <p>
                the associated homogeneous system. </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>Next assume that <m>\vec{h}</m> satisfies (<xref ref="eq-nhs" />). Then we show
                that <m>\vec{h}+\vec{p}</m> satisfies: </p>

              <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>a_{i,1} (h_1+p_1)\amp + a_{i,2} (h_2+p_2) + \cdots + a_{i,n} (h_n+p_n)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = a_{i,1} h_1 + a_{i,2} h_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} h_n + </mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp \qquad a_{i,1} p_1 + a_{i,2} p_2 + \cdots + a_{i,n} p_n </mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 0 + b_i = b_i</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>

              <p> satisfies (<xref ref="eq-nhs" />).</p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>


    <p>As a summary of this section, the title </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        \text{Solution} = \text{Particular} + \text{Homogeneous}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      and if we can find any particular solution and add it to the homogeneous solution, then we
      have the full solution.
    </p>

    <table>
      <title>Summary of Solutions</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell halign="center" colspan="2">number of solutions of the</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell halign="center" colspan="2" bottom="minor">associated homogeneous system</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="center">particular</cell>
          <cell right="minor" bottom="minor"></cell>
          <cell bottom="minor">one</cell>
          <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">infinitely many</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="center" right="minor">solution</cell>
          <cell right="minor">yes</cell>
          <cell>unique solution</cell>
          <cell>infinitely many solutions</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="center" right="minor">exists?</cell>
          <cell right="minor" bottom="minor">no</cell>
          <cell>no solutions</cell>
          <cell>no solutions</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sect-solving-homogeneous-linear-systems">
    <title>Solving homogeneous Linear Systems</title>


    <p> A homogeneous linear system can be solved in a reasonably efficient manner. Consider the
      system: </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x_1 -2x_2 + x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
        <mrow>3x_1 + 0x_2 -2x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
        <mrow>0x_1 + 6x_2 -5x_3 \amp = 0</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      and if we write down the augmented coefficient matrix we get:
    </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
        1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        3 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 6 \amp -5 \amp 0
        \end{array}\right]
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      If we perform row operations on this matrix, then the 4th column (right hand side of the
      linear system), will remain zero, so instead of including this vector, we'll perform row
      operations only on the first three columns:
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
          3 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
          0 \amp 6 \amp -5
          \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow>-3 R_1 + R_2 \rightarrow R_2 \qquad \amp
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 6 \amp -5 \\
          0 \amp 6 \amp -5
          \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        <mrow>-R_2 -R_3 \rightarrow R_3 \qquad \amp
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 6 \amp -5 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      which is now in echelon form. To find the solution, we will write down the top two
      equations, recalling that the right hand side is 0.
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x_1 -2x_2+x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
        <mrow>6x_2-5x_3 \amp = 0, </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p> solving the second equation for <m>x_2</m> results in </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        x_2 = \frac{5}{6} x_3
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      and then substitute this into the first equation:
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x_1 - 2\biggl(\frac{5}{6} x_3 \biggr) + x_3 \amp = 0 </mrow>
        <mrow>x_1 -\frac{2}{3} x_3 </mrow>
        <mrow>x_1 \amp = \frac{2}{3} x_3</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      and writing the solution in vector form is
    </p>

    <p>
      <me>
        \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
        2/3 \\ 5/6 \\ 1
        \end{bmatrix} x_3 \; | \; x_3 \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
      </me>
    </p>

</subsection>


<subsection>
  <title>Singular and Nonsingular Matrices</title>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>A square matrix <m>A</m> is <term>nonsingular</term> if it is a matrix of coefficients of a
        homogeneous linear system with the unique solution <m>\vec{0}</m>. Otherwise it is <term>
        singular</term>, that is the associated homogeneous system has a solution set with an
        infinite number of points.</p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>The associated linear system in Example <xref ref="ex-nh-and-homo" /> has an infinite
        number of solutions, therefore the matrix</p>

      <p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
          1 \amp 4 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>is singular. </p>

      <p>The linear system </p>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>4x_1 - x_3 \amp = 0, </mrow>
          <mrow>x_1+3x_2 +2x_3 \amp = 3, </mrow>
          <mrow>3x_2 + 5x_3 \amp = 14.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        was shown above to have a unique solution, thus the associated homogeneous
        system also has a unique solution which implies that the matrix </p>

      <p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
          4 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
          1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        is nonsingular. </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>Is the matrix</p>

      <p>
        <me> \begin{bmatrix}
          3 \amp 2 \\
          1 \amp 4
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        singular or nonsingular? </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>

      <p>
        We can consider the elements of the matrix to be the coefficients of a homogeneous linear
        system and find its solution. Thus we reduce
      </p>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\left[\begin{array}{rr|r}
            3 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            1 \amp 4 \amp 0
            \end{array}\right] </mrow>
          <mrow>-R_1 + 3R_2 \rightarrow R_2 \qquad
            \left[\begin{array}{rr|r}
            3 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 10 \amp 0
            \end{array}\right] </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p> which is now in echelon form. The last equation <m>10y=0</m> implies <m>y=0</m> and the
        top row can be written as <m>3x+2y=0</m> or <m>3x=0</m> or <m>x=0</m>, thus this has the
        unique solution <m>(0,0)</m>. This implies that the original matrix is nonsingular. </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</subsection>
</section>